[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(14) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "I was a derision.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The personal experience of the prophet breaks through the succession of imagery. The arrows that pierced to the quick were the taunts of the mockers who derided him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 20:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). “Their song.” (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 30:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Lamentations 3:14-19",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Lamentations 3:14-19",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I was a derision to all my people ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— To all the wicked among them, who made themselves merry with the prophet’s griefs and the public judgments; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and their song all the day — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "נגינתם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", their instrument of music. The word, says Blaney, “is commonly rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "their song; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "but I rather think it means a subject upon which they played, as upon a musical instrument, for their diversion.” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He hath filled me with bitterness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — A bitter sense of these calamities. God has access to the spirit, and can so imbitter it, as thereby to imbitter all enjoyments; as when the stomach is foul, whatever is eaten becomes acid in it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He hath made me drunken with wormwood — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, so intoxicated me with the sense of my afflictions, that I know not what to say or do. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He hath broken my teeth with gravel- stones — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hath mingled gravel with my bread, so that my teeth are broken with it, and what I eat is neither pleasant nor nourishing. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He hath covered me with ashes — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As mourners were wont to be; or, as some render ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "הכפישׁני אפר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he hath laid me low, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "made me wallow, in ashes, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "namely, because of great sorrow and grief. These expressions imply the height of misery; that he received no comfort or refreshment from any thing. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "I said, My strength, my hope is gone — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "I even began to despair of God’s mercy; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "remembering my affliction — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Reflecting on all the miseries and hardships I had suffered. Without doubt it was his infirmity to think and speak thus, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 77:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) for with God there is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "everlasting strength, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and he is his people’s never-failing hope, whatever they may suspect to the contrary.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3:1-20 The prophet relates the more gloomy and discouraging part of his experience, and how he found support and relief. In the time of his trial the Lord had become terrible to him. It was an affliction that was misery itself; for sin makes the cup of affliction a bitter cup. The struggle between unbelief and faith is often very severe. But the weakest believer is wrong, if he thinks that his strength and hope are perished from the Lord.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Metaphor is dropped, and Jeremiah shows the real nature of the arrows which rankled in him so deeply.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "14. (Jer 20:7).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "their song—(Ps 69:12). Jeremiah herein was a type of Messiah. \"All my people\" (Joh 1:11).",
        "children": []
      }
